A quick-start guide to using GitHub for version control and collaboration.



## âœ… 1. Create a GitHub Account
- Go to: [https://github.com](https://github.com)
- Sign up with your email
- Set a username and password
- Verify your email



## âœ… 2. Install Git
- Download from: [https://git-scm.com/downloads](https://git-scm.com/downloads)
- Install with default settings
- Open Git Bash or terminal

---

## âœ… 3. Set Up Git (One-Time Only)

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your@email.com"


âœ… 4. Create a Repository
Go to your GitHub profile

Click "New" in the Repositories tab

Fill in:

Repository name (e.g., my-project)

Visibility: Public or Private

Optionally: Initialize with a README

Click "Create repository"

âœ… 5. Clone the Repository
bash
Copy
Edit
git clone https://github.com/your-username/my-project.git
cd my-project


âœ… 6. Add/Edit Your Project Files
Use a code editor (e.g., VS Code)

Add or change files inside the folder

âœ… 7. Track & Push Changes

git add .                    # Track all changes
git commit -m "your message" # Save changes with message
git push origin main         # Push to GitHub
âœ… 8. Pull Latest Changes

git pull origin main

âœ… 9. Create a New Branch (Optional)

git checkout -b feature-branch
# make changes
git push origin feature-branch


âœ… 10. Open a Pull Request
Go to your repository on GitHub

Click "Compare & pull request"

Review, comment, and merge
